The paper explores the academic status and usage patterns of Mendeley users in terms of subject fields, citation, and readership impact. The study focuses on the filtering capacity of Mendeley readership counts compared to journal citation scores in detecting highly cited WoS publications. This study is relevant to several sub-categories of computer science, including digital libraries (cs.DL), information retrieval (cs.IR), social and information networks (cs.SI), cryptography and security (cs.CR), and computers and society (cs.CY).
